neteenth Amendment in 1920, Allison K. Lange explores how suffragists pioneered one of the first extensive visual campaigns in modern American history. She shows how pictures, from early engravings and photographs to colorful posters, proved central to suffragists’ efforts to change expectations for women, fighting back against the accepted norms of their times. In seeking to transform notions of womanhood and win the right to vote, white suffragists emphasized the compatibility of voting and motherhood, while Sojourner Truth and other leading suffragists of color employed pictures to secure respect and authority. Picturing Political Power demonstrates the centrality of visual politics to American women’s campaigns throughout the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, revealing the power of images to change history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aFirst-wave feminism. 0aGraphic artsxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aSuffragistszUnited StatesxPortraits. 0aWomen in art. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aWomenxSuffragezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxPortraits. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aUnited States history.  agender.  ahistory.  aimages.  apolitics.  asuffrage.  avisual culture.  awomen's history.  awomen's rights.  awomen's suffrage movement.  awomen's voting rights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP Frontlist eBook-Package